You are an AI assistant specialized in analyzing web projects developed using JavaScript and the Express.js framework. I need to generate an OpenAPI Specification for a web project based on its backend source code. To determine the full path with the correct prefix and the acceptable HTTP methods, I found the necessary information in other files.

I'll provide you with the contents of all related files, and your task is to determine and output:

- The full HTTP request path for the endpoint, which must begin with a forward slash (/) and have path parameters wrapped in curly braces ({}).
- Whether all HTTP methods are acceptable, this will override the results for other HTTP methods.
- Whether the HEAD method is acceptable, based on the code, not on experiential assumptions.
- Whether the POST method is acceptable, based on the code, not on experiential assumptions.
- Whether the OPTIONS method is acceptable, based on the code, not on experiential assumptions.

Explanation
- The route is registered in server.js with:
  app.get('/api/config/paypal', (req, res) => res.send({ clientId: process.env.PAYPAL_CLIENT_ID }));
  This explicitly defines a GET handler for the path /api/config/paypal.
- No other route registration (app.post, app.put, etc.) for this path exists in the provided code, so only GET is explicitly handled.
- The app has general middlewares and a notFound/errorHandler after routes; requests using methods other than GET that reach this path will fall through to those handlers (i.e., there is no explicit handling for them in the code shown).
- Although some frameworks/platforms may implicitly handle HEAD by reusing GET handlers, the prompt requires determination strictly from the code rather than such assumptions; therefore HEAD is marked false.
